The DataFrame is Spark's primary high-level API for structured data. It combines the familiarity of a table — named columns, types, SQL-style operations — with the distributed execution model of Spark. Understanding DataFrames deeply is the single biggest skill for the Databricks Associate exam and real-world Spark work.

The Spark API Hierarchy.

Spark gives you three ways to express computations: SQL, the DataFrame and Dataset API, and the RDD API.

SQL and DataFrame and Dataset all go through the Catalyst optimizer and the Tungsten execution engine — they produce identical execution plans. It does not matter whether you write a SQL query string or chain DataFrame method calls; the end result is the same optimized physical plan.

The RDD API bypasses Catalyst entirely. There is no automatic optimization — you are responsible for writing an efficient plan yourself.

In Python, DataFrame is the only high-level option. Dataset of T, which is a typed collection parameterized by a Scala or Java class, is only available in Scala and Java. In fact, DataFrame is simply an alias for Dataset of Row — they are the same thing.

DataFrame Structure.

A DataFrame is a distributed table. It has a schema — column names and their data types — and it has rows, split across partitions on executor nodes.

Four key properties define a DataFrame. It is immutable — every transformation returns a new DataFrame and leaves the original untouched. It is lazily evaluated — transformations build an execution plan but nothing runs until you call an action. It is schema-enforced — every row is required to match the same column types. And it is partitioned — the rows are divided across partitions so they can be processed in parallel.

The Schema — StructType and StructField.

The schema describes the structure of the DataFrame. In PySpark you define it using StructType as the container and StructField for each column.

Each StructField takes three arguments: the column name as a string, the data type — such as LongType, StringType, IntegerType, BooleanType, DoubleType, DateType, TimestampType, ArrayType, or MapType — and a nullable flag indicating whether the column can contain null values.

Spark also accepts a DDL string as a shorthand. For example, "id LONG NOT NULL, name STRING, age INT, active BOOLEAN" defines the same four-column schema. The DDL form is often more concise for simple schemas.

Always prefer an explicit schema over schema inference. Inference is convenient, but it requires Spark to scan a sample of the data to guess types, which is slower and can produce unexpected results — for example, inferring an integer column as a long, or a date column as a string.

Creating DataFrames.

There are four common ways to create a DataFrame.

The first is from a Python list using spark.createDataFrame, passing the list and a schema. You can pass the StructType schema object or a DDL string or a list of column name strings.

The second is schema inference — pass a list of column names instead of a full schema and Spark infers the types. Convenient for quick experiments, but use explicit schemas in production.

The third is spark.range, which generates a DataFrame of consecutive integers. It accepts a stop value, or a start, stop, and step. It is the fastest way to create test data.

The fourth is from a pandas DataFrame using spark.createDataFrame. Spark maps pandas dtypes to Spark types automatically. Be aware that this collects the pandas data on the driver and distributes it — avoid for large datasets.

Exploring a DataFrame.

Several methods help you understand a DataFrame's contents and structure.

count returns the number of rows. columns returns the list of column name strings. dtypes returns a list of column name and type string pairs. rdd.getNumPartitions tells you how many partitions the DataFrame has.

printSchema prints the column names, types, and nullability in a readable tree format — use this to verify your schema is what you expect.

describe of one or more column names returns a summary statistics DataFrame with count, mean, standard deviation, min, and max for each column.

show prints the first twenty rows in a formatted table. You can pass a number to control how many rows to show, and set truncate to False to see full values without cutting them off.

Selecting Columns.

There are four ways to reference a column in PySpark and they are largely interchangeable.

The string form — just the column name as a string — is the simplest and works for most situations.

The col function from pyspark.sql.functions returns a Column object. This is the preferred form when you need to apply functions to the column, chain operations, or combine expressions.

The DataFrame bracket syntax — df of "name" in brackets — also returns a Column object and ties it explicitly to the DataFrame. This avoids ambiguity when joining two DataFrames that have columns with the same name.

The dot syntax — df dot name — is convenient for interactive use but breaks if the column name contains spaces or matches a Python reserved word.

The expr function accepts a SQL expression string and returns a Column. It is useful for complex expressions that are easier to write in SQL than as method chains, such as "age plus 5 AS age_in_5_years".

The select method accepts any mix of these forms and returns a new DataFrame with only the specified columns.

Adding, Renaming, and Dropping Columns.

withColumn adds a new column or replaces an existing one if the name already exists. It takes the column name as a string and a Column expression. Common patterns include using when and otherwise for conditional logic, calling built-in functions like upper or lower on existing columns, and using lit to add a column of a constant literal value.

withColumnRenamed renames a column — it takes the old name and the new name.

drop removes one or more columns by name and returns the DataFrame without them.

Filtering Rows.

filter and where are identical — use whichever reads more naturally. Both accept either a Column expression or a SQL expression string.

When combining multiple conditions, use the ampersand operator for AND and the pipe operator for OR and the tilde operator for NOT. Always wrap each individual condition in parentheses — without them Python's operator precedence will produce incorrect results.

isin checks whether a column's value is in a given list. Negate it with the tilde operator to get NOT isin.

Handling Nulls.

Nulls require special handling in Spark because standard equality checks do not work for null — null equals null returns null, not true.

isNull and isNotNull are the correct way to filter null and non-null rows respectively.

dropna removes rows that contain null values. By default it drops any row with at least one null. Pass a subset argument with a list of column names to only check those columns.

fillna replaces null values. Pass a dictionary mapping column names to replacement values to fill different columns with different values.

coalesce from pyspark.sql.functions returns the first non-null value from a list of columns. It is useful for creating a fallback column — for example, return the name column if it is not null, otherwise return the string "N/A".

Type Casting.

The cast method converts a column to a different type. You can pass a type object such as DoubleType, or a DDL string such as "string" or "double". The DDL string form is often more readable.

Sorting and Deduplication.

orderBy and sort are synonyms. Both accept column names or Column expressions. Call dot desc on a Column expression for descending order. For multi-column sorting, pass multiple columns — Spark sorts by each in order.

distinct removes duplicate rows across all columns. It causes a shuffle because Spark must compare records across partitions. dropDuplicates does the same but lets you specify which columns to consider — rows are considered duplicates if the values in those columns match, even if other columns differ.

Converting Between APIs.

toPandas collects all rows to the driver and converts them to a pandas DataFrame. Only use this on small DataFrames — collecting a large distributed dataset to the driver will exhaust its memory.

df.rdd returns the underlying RDD of Row objects. Each Row behaves like a named tuple — you access fields by name. This is the bridge when you need low-level RDD operations on structured data.

Going the other direction, you can wrap an RDD of Row objects in spark.createDataFrame to get a DataFrame back.

Summary.

A DataFrame is a distributed table with a schema — immutable, lazily evaluated, and partitioned across executors.

SQL, DataFrame, and Dataset APIs all go through Catalyst and produce identical execution plans. RDD bypasses Catalyst.

Define schemas with StructType and StructField, or as a DDL string. Explicit schemas are faster and safer than inferred ones.

Reference columns with strings, col, bracket syntax, or expr. Use col when applying functions.

withColumn adds or replaces a column. withColumnRenamed renames. drop removes.

filter and where are identical. Combine conditions with ampersand for AND, pipe for OR, tilde for NOT — always parenthesise each condition.

Handle nulls with isNull, isNotNull, dropna, fillna, and coalesce.

toPandas collects to the driver — only use on small DataFrames. df.rdd gives the underlying RDD when you need low-level control.
